1 (2) DOES NOT SPEAK ENGLISH AS A PRIMARY LANGUAGE; AND
2 (3) SPEAKS, READS, OR UNDERSTANDS THE ENGLISH LANGUAGE
3 LESS THAN “VERY WELL”, AS REPORTED IN AVAILABLE U.S. CENSUS BUREAU DATA
4 OR DATA OF COMPARABLE QUALITY COLLECTED BY A PUBLIC OFFICE.
5 15.5–102.
6 (A) SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION, THE STATE BOARD
7 SHALL DETERMINE WHETHER THERE IS A SIGNIFICANT AND SUBSTANTIAL NEED
8 FOR LANGUAGE–RELATED ASSISTANCE IN ONE OR MORE LANGUAGES OTHER THAN
9 ENGLISH BY A LOCAL BOARD DURING AN ELECTION.
10 (B) THE STATE BOARD SHALL DETERMINE THAT A SIGNIFICANT AND
11 SUBSTANTIAL NEED FOR LANGUAGE–RELATED ASSISTANCE BY A LOCAL BOARD
12 DURING AN ELECTION EXISTS IN A COUNTY IF, BASED ON THE BEST AVAILABLE
13 DATA, INCLUDING INFORMATION FROM THE U.S. CENSUS BUREAU’S AMERICAN
14 COMMUNITY SURVEY OR DATA OF COMPARABLE QUALITY COLLECTED BY A PUBLIC
15 OFFICE:
16 (1) MORE THAN 2%, BUT IN NO INSTANCE FEWER THAN 100
17 INDIVIDUALS, OF THE VOTING AGE POPULATION OF THE COUNTY:
18 (I) USE A SINGLE SHARED LANGUAGE OTHER THAN ENGLISH;
19 AND
20 (II) HAVE LIMITED ENGLISH PROFICIENCY; OR
21 (2) MORE THAN 4,000 INDIVIDUALS OF THE VOTING AGE POPULATION
22 OF THE COUNTY USE A SINGLE SHARED LANGUAGE OTHER THAN ENGLISH AND HAVE
23 LIMITED ENGLISH PROFICIENCY.
24 (C) THE STATE BOARD MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS THAT ESTABLISH
25 ADDITIONAL CRITERIA FOR DETERMINING WHETHER A SIGNIFICANT AND
26 SUBSTANTIAL NEED FOR LANGUAGE–RELATED ASSISTANCE BY A LOCAL BOARD
27 DURING AN ELECTION EXISTS IN A COUNTY.
28 15.5–103.
29 (A) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2026, AND EVERY 2 YEARS THEREAFTER,
30 THE STATE BOARD SHALL PUBLISH AND MAINTAIN ON ITS WEBSITE A LIST OF:

