5 CORRESPONDING ENGLISH LANGUAGE MATERIALS.
6 (2) ALL TRANSLATIONS SHALL CONVEY THE INTENT AND ESSENTIAL
7 MEANING OF THE ORIGINAL TEXT OR COMMUNICATION AND MAY NOT SOLELY RELY
8 ON AUTOMATIC ELECTRONIC TRANSLATION SERVICES, INCLUDING MACHINE
9 TRANSLATION OR OTHER ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE APPLICATIONS.
10 (3) (I) IN ADDITION TO THE OTHER REQUIREMENTS OF THIS
11 SECTION, LANGUAGE–RELATED ASSISTANCE SHALL INCLUDE THE PRESENCE OF
12 BILINGUAL ELECTION JUDGES WHERE AVAILABLE.
13 (II) A LOCAL BOARD SHALL MAKE REASONABLE EFFORTS TO
14 RECRUIT ELECTION JUDGES WHO ARE FLUENT IN EACH LANGUAGE DESIGNATED BY
15 THE STATE BOARD UNDER § 15.5–102 OF THIS TITLE, INCLUDING BY USING NOTICES
16 IN NEWSPAPERS, RADIO, TELEVISION, AND OTHER FORMS OF MEDIA, WITH A
17 PARTICULAR FOCUS ON MEDIA THAT SERVE NON–ENGLISH–SPEAKING CITIZENS IN
18 THE COUNTY.
19 (III) BILINGUAL ELECTION JUDGES SHALL PROVIDE DIRECT
20 ASSISTANCE TO VOTERS WHO HAVE LIMITED ENGLISH PROFICIENCY AND MAY NOT
21 ATTEMPT TO INTERPRET OR TRANSLATE ENGLISH LANGUAGE MATERIALS.
22 (E) THIS SECTION MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED TO PREVENT A LOCAL BOARD
23 FROM VOLUNTARILY PROVIDING LANGUAGE–RELATED ASSISTANCE IN ADDITION TO
24 THE ASSISTANCE REQUIRED BY THIS TITLE.
